[1
Date: Wed, 17 Jun 1998 16:32:26 -0400
From: Robin L. Travers, M.D. <rtravers@bu.edu>

I find these reports interesting and alarming. As a dermatologist, I see
children with uncomplicated hand, foot, and mouth disease frequently during
the summer months. I rarely consider viral typing. I practice in a
community with a large immigrant population, many of whom are recent
immigrants.
Should I consider viral typing for patients who present with uncomplicated
hand, foot, and mouth disease as a surveillance measure? If so, what is
the appropriate collection method, and to whom should the samples be sent?
--
Robin L. Travers, MD
Department of Dermatology and Continuing Medical Education
Boston University School of Medicine
e-mail: rtravers@bu.edu
