[2
Date: Wed, 17 Jun 1998 22:42:58 +0700
From: David Hipgrave <hipgrave@netnam.org.vn>

I am a Paediatrician working on a public health project, based here in
Hanoi, Viet Nam. At present I believe I am the only expatriate
paediatrician doing any clinical work here, and I am often asked to see the
children of other foreign residents. I also have young children of my own.
I have been reading the items on this epidemic with great interest and a
little nervousness as we are so close to Taiwan and the numbers are so high
that it seems inevitable that we will see cases here.
None of the postings have given much clinical information about how the
majority of cases (the non-fatal ones) have been presenting, or how those
who died looked early in their illness. This month I have seen 2 children
(siblings) who presented with oral ulcers, high fever and diarrhoea 10 days
after a trip to Hong Kong. One was quite sick - pale and lethargic but
normotensive, before improving spontaneously, and I am
wondering if they brought this illness with them from Hong Kong. There
have also been cases of classical hand, foot and mouth disease in late April.
I would appreciate any Taiwanese clinician subscribers to ProMED-mail
posting a description of the typical clinical presentation of the cases
they have seen, any danger signs common to those who deteriorated,
incubation period for disease in contacts of those who were sick
previously, natural history of illness in those in whom the illness
resolved etc. I would have thought that with 300 000 cases, 30 (or 38)
deaths and supposedly a single aetiological agent a pattern would be emerging.
--
Dr David Hipgrave, FRACP
Project Manager
Strengthening Immunisation and Malaria Control Project
PATH - Macfarlane Burnet Centre - University of Melbourne
Box 252, I.P.O.
Hanoi, Viet Nam
Ph. 84 4 766 0484
Fax 84 4 766 0486
email: hipgrave@netnam.org.vn
