[3
Date: Wed, 17 Jun 1998 19:17:35 +0800 (MYT)
From: Amar & Im <amimar@pc.jaring.my>

Having had a small hand in the epidemic in Malaysia (managed some of the
children in Sarawak that died), I would be grateful if the Taiwan
paediatricians could share with us what their therapeutic options are
currently. Are they having any success? We saw very few children whom we
thought we had salvaged.
During the height of our epidemic the following were considered useful:
1. IV gamma globulin (1-2 g/kg) single dose
2. High dose inotropes
3. Very close clinical and HR monitoring using electronic means (although
this only told us who was at risk of dying but not what to do)
4. Conventional intensive care support
IV acyclovir was tried, for what it is worth, but was mainly motivated by
frustration at not being able to do much.
Some tried high dose steroids but generally we felt they were not useful.
We want to learn from the Taiwan epidemic to prepare for any further cases.
Our prayers with your children & families.
--
Dr Amar HSS
Consultant Paediatrician
Ipoh, Malaysia
e-mail: amimar@pc.jaring.my
